carbonemission <- gapminder %>% 
  group_by(co2) %>% 
  filter(name == "United States of America" |name == "China" | name == "India" |
           name == "Japan" | name =="Italy") 

ggplot(carbonemission) +
  geom_col(aes(x = name, y = co2))
## Warning: Removed 17 rows containing missing values (`position_stack()`).

Of these 5 countires, the US has the most carbon emissions, then followed by China. Italy has the least CO2 emissions in comparison to the rest.

carbonemissionpercap <- gapminder %>% 
  group_by(co2_PC) %>% 
  filter(name == "United States of America" |name == "China" | name == "India" |
           name == "Japan" | name =="Italy") 

ggplot(carbonemissionpercap) +
  geom_col(aes(x = name, y = co2_PC))
## Warning: Removed 17 rows containing missing values (`position_stack()`).

The United states still has the most carbon emissions per capita, meaning that the average person in America will emit more CO2 than the average person of any of the remaining countries. Indias CO2 emission per capita is the lowest because they dont emit a lot of CO2 in comparison to the US and China and they have a much higher population among most countries.
